<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-987-730  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 987 730.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Data Communications  Nov 1989 v18 n15 p214(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Specs maniacs. (the relative importance of data communicationsspecifications) (commentary) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Weiss, Jeffrey.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The increasing reliance of data communications managers onequipment connecting local area networks over wide area networks,particularly remote bridges and routers, makes them more relianton vendor-published specifications for these products.andO;Unfortunately, few of the published specs represent performance inreal situations.andP;  Vendor claims about Ethernet are used toillustrate what is called creative use of numbers by sellers.andP;  Themost minimum-length packets that can be transferred across anEthernet WAN bridge is about 2,900 per second, consideringdegradation, but one bridge vendor claims a link-filtering rate of28,000 packets per second, and another claims a rate of 16,000packets per second.andP;  Network managers can avoid the foibles ofspecsmanship by emphasizing fundamentals: response time of aspecific configuration, required response time and performanceunder different load conditions.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data CommunicationsCommunications ManagementSpecificationsLocal Area NetworksNetwork ManagementTestingHardware Selection.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>